<HEADLINE>
<P>
CUTTING U.S. DEFENSE SPENDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The unfolding major decline in worldwide communism should strikingly improve 
the military security of the United States. However, even if we receive a 
"peace" dividend because of reduced military expenditures, our country might 
face tougher economic competition. 
</P>
<P>
Some of those countries converting from communism to capitalism would become 
far more competitive in a global economy. 
</P>
<P>
At the end of World War II, the U.S. dominated the world economy, but has seen 
its share of the world gross national product slip with the rise of other 
capitalist economies out of the ashes of war. 
</P>
<P>
Aren't we in for a new wave of hard-nosed competitors out of the ashes of 
communism? 
</P>
<P>
What if a number of these new capitalists follow Japan's post-war philosophy of 
high savings and investment rates, in order to favor a rapid buildup in 
production capacity? If so, are we willing to curtail our profligate consumer 
borrowing and spending habits in order to compete under the new reality? 
</P>
<P>
FLOYD A. OLIVER 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
