<HEADLINE>
<P>
GRAMMAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jerry Colburn argues that low achievement in writing is the result of "junking 
the grammar lesson" and a failure to correct errors ("The Ostrich Method of 
English Grammar," California Commentary, Nov. 20). Research over several 
decades, however, has shown that direct teaching of grammar and error 
correction has little or no effect on student writing. The research does show 
that students who read more read better, write better, have larger 
vocabularies, and even do better on grammar tests. Our students need good 
literature programs and improved school libraries, not more sentence 
diagramming. 
</P>
<P>
STEPHEN KRASHEN 
</P>
<P>
Professor of Linguistics 
</P>
<P>
USC 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
