433 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: TEST WHAT YOU KNOW ABOUT FEAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Should children be afraid? How much do you know about normal and abnormal fears 
in children? Here's true-or-false test on this subject. 
</P>
<P>
1. -- A healthy child has no fears. 
</P>
<P>
2. -- The child who fears that every cold may turn into pneumonia is 
intelligent, not unhealthy. 
</P>
<P>
3. -- The young child's fears are basically the same today as they were in the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
4. -- If a 7-, 8- or 9-year-old expresses a fear of strangers or robbers, 
parents should be concerned, because chances are this is an indication of 
neuroses. 
</P>
<P>
5. -- Parents can help reduce the level of a child's anxieties about almost any 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
6. -- If a child has fears, it may be an indication that he's less intelligent 
than the child without fears. 
</P>
<P>
7. -- Parents should protect their children but not worry them about so-called 
"bad" people who might take advantage of them. 
</P>
<P>
8. -- The greatest fears and worries of 15-year-olds center on whether or not 
their world will be destroyed by nuclear war. 
</P>
<P>
ANSWERS: 
</P>
<P>
1. -- FALSE. Everyone needs to have some fears. Without them no one would 
survive, for we would take too many foolish risks that could destroy us. 
</P>
<P>
2. -- FALSE. This is an unrealistic fear that may be an early indication of 
hypochondria. This shows an excessive preoccupation with sickness and may be 
reflecting a parent's anxiety. 
</P>
<P>
3. -- TRUE. Children between the ages of 4 and 7 fear unknown things and bad 
things. 
</P>
<P>
4. -- FALSE. These are normal anxieties in children of that age, because 
they're more aware of things happening in the neighborhood and community. 
</P>
<P>
5. -- TRUE. They can do this by being calm and rational themselves and by 
talking about specific problems that concern the youngster. Children's fears 
often reflect their parents' anxiety levels. 
</P>
<P>
6. -- FALSE. Actually, a child who is fearful is apt to be more intelligent 
because he or she is more aware of the dangers in the world and the 
environment. 
</P>
<P>
7. -- FALSE. Of course parents should protect their children, but part of the 
protection is to warn them that all strangers may not be nice. They should know 
how to protect themselves from sexual abuse just as they should know about the 
importance of obeying traffic rules. 
</P>
<P>
8. -- FALSE. Probably the biggest fear and anxiety of 15-year-olds is related 
to sex. By this age, many children have been pressured by peers either to have 
or not to have sex. Those who do may feel guilty and fearful of the 
consequences, and those who don't may worry about being liked by peers and 
being considered "normal." 
</P>
<P>
If you answered six questions correctly, you're better informed than most on 
this subject. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112989-0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 141104 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 29, 1989, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part E; Page 7; Column 4; View Desk 
</P>
