<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Armed state officials had no right to set up a "riverblock" to stop and search 
people canoeing on the Saco River, Maine's Supreme Court ruled. Two state 
agencies set up the riverblocks on three weekends in 1988 to try to stop rowdy 
and illegal conduct. The justices agreed unanimously with a lower court judge 
who said the searches violated the federal and state constitutions. The ruling 
came in a suit by Daniel and Jarlene Hatfield of Rochester, N.H., who were 
searched extensively. 
