<HEADLINE>
<P>
JAMES FLANIGAN: COLD WAR'S END MAY OPEN DOORS FOR DEFENSE WORKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES FLANIGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Armed Services employ 2.1 million people in uniform and an additional 
1 million civilians. In addition, more than 2 million people work for 
aerospace-defense companies and thus stand to be affected by cuts in the 
defense budget. 
</P>
<P>
And there is a multiplier effect among the millions more who work for the 
non-defense firms that supply those aerospace companies with everything from 
paper clips to gasoline. Add them all up, and it's understandable that 
communities in practically every state are apprehensive about cuts in the 
defense budget, even as they hail the end of the Cold War and tell pollster 
Louis Harris that they favor reduced military spending. Fear of unemployment 
clouds even a hope as bright as peace. 
</P>
<P>
The record is not reassuring: The end of World War I in November, 1918, led to 
a severe economic downturn in 1920. The economy did better in the transition to 
peace after World War II, but it had help from the buildup of peacetime defense 
industry -- the advanced aircraft and high-tech weaponry programs that are now 
faced with winding down. 
</P>
<P>
So what's likely to happen to the economy this time? Things will be better than 
communities fear today -- maybe far better. Two things to keep in mind are that 
simple inertia will ease the economy's transition and that people don't stop 
thinking just because defense money stops pumping -- hosts of skilled workers 
in defense may find great opportunities in commercial projects. 
</P>
<P>
First inertia. Cutbacks won't happen as swiftly as feared. "Politics won't 
allow dramatic cuts to happen," says analyst Michael Lauer of Kidder, Peabody 
&amp; Co., who notes that the New York congressional delegation's lobbying has 
kept production of the Navy F-14D fighter plane going at Long Island's Grumman 
Aircraft. Similar politicking will at least extend the transition from growing 
to shrinking defense budgets. 
</P>
<P>
Then, too, the amount of the $286-billion budget's ultimate shrinkage is a good 
question. Reports are that $180 billion will be cut from defense budgets during 
fiscal years 1992 to 1994 and that defense spending will be reduced from 6% of 
the U.S. gross national product -- now $5.13 trillion -- to 4% by 1994. But by 
that time the GNP will have grown to nearly $6 trillion -- which indicates an 
annual defense budget roughly $40 billion less than today's. 
</P>
<P>
Translation: There will be cuts in defense spending, but not enough to cause an 
economic depression. In a nutshell, the defense industry is entering a long 
period of no-growth. "It will just be a tougher business for aerospace-defense 
companies," says analyst Wolfgang Demisch of UBS Securities. "They'll have to 
keep their eye on the ball." 
</P>
<P>
Some programs will be canceled: Analysts suggest the B-2 bomber will be a 
sacrificial pawn in negotiations to get the Soviets to give up mobile missiles. 
Some programs will be expanded: Surveillance satellites will continue to be 
built, perhaps even more so in an era when disarmament agreements need 
verification. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, expect some troops to come home from Europe and expect the armed 
forces to be reduced by 500,000 or so -- but not to swell the ranks of the 
unemployed. "Most military people are confident they'll find jobs," says a 
military analyst. "They're trained people, who have proved themselves in the 
military, and we have a labor-short economy." 
</P>
<P>
Even more positive are the possibilities that await the thousands of engineers 
working in defense firms. If their projects get canceled or their departments 
are cut back, they could find a welcome in commercial industry, even the chance 
to found their own business, with the aid of venture capital. "We're eager to 
listen and talk to people in aerospace about ideas, or even better about 
setting up a business," says Michael Moritz, a partner in Sequoia Capital, a 
venture capital firm in Menlo Park. 
</P>
<P>
Other venture capital firms, such as Sevin-Rosen Management in Dallas and New 
York and Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield &amp; Byers of San Francisco and Palo Alto, 
hope to see a new breed of entrepreneurs come out of defense work -- although 
they admit that the idea is new and unfamiliar. The conventional thinking is 
that there is no connection between commercial industry and what one does in 
defense work -- or as one analyst puts it, "You can't easily sell knowledge of 
wing-based gun systems." 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps not, concedes Sequoia Capital's Moritz, "but there's certainly a call 
for advanced semiconductor skills and skills in telecommunications and 
imaging." 
</P>
<P>
"A lot of good optics work is done in the military -- space lasers, pop-up 
computer displays -- while the commercial field is crying out for optical 
engineers," says Floyd Kwamme, a partner in the Kleiner, Perkins firm. "I see 
engineering talent from the defense field taking jobs in commercial start-up 
firms and then perhaps founding their own company when the next product comes 
along." 
</P>
<P>
A heady vision. "It won't take many guys coming out of Rockwell or McDonnell or 
the other dinosaurs to give their colleagues ideas," says a venture capital 
type. The message: The economy's need for weapons may diminish but not its need 
for brains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DEFENSE INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; LAYOFFS; DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE (U.S.) -- 
BUDGET; UNITED STATES -- ARMED FORCES; AEROSPACE INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; 
UNITED STATES -- ECONOMY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112989-0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 141283 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 29, 1989, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 1; Column 2; Financial Desk 
</P>
