<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
COCA-COLA LIGHTS UP MOSCOW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In one more sign of changing times in the Soviet Union, officials of the 
Coca-Cola Co. today lighted the country's first neon advertising billboard in 
Moscow's Pushkin Square. 
</P>
<P>
E. Neville Isdell, Coca-Cola senior vice president, turned a switch 
illuminating the red neon sign in a ceremony in the square. 
</P>
<P>
The sign, which measures about 20 by 40 feet, features the world's best-known 
trademark in a moving neon display, along with the current time and 
temperature. Each day, tens of thousands of people pass through Pushkin Square, 
one of Moscow's busiest intersections. 
</P>
<P>
Similar signs are located in New York City, London, Tokyo and Sydney, 
Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
