<P>
'DORF' GOES TO COURT AND WINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Los Angeles judge ruled that the latest sports videotape featuring comedian 
Tim Conway's diminutive "Dorf" character can be shipped to stores despite a 
distributor's claim that it was unfairly cut out of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
Superior Court Judge Kurt J. Lewin ruled Tuesday that J2 Communications Inc. 
has the first right of refusal for distribution of "Dorf" videos only when they 
are produced by Longshot Enterprises Inc., of which Conway is the majority 
owner. Lewin said the story idea and production of the new "Dorf Goes Auto 
Racing" came from Liaison East Inc., so the distribution contract between J2 
and Longshot does not apply. 
</P>
<P>
J2 distributed the first three "Dorf" videos, "Dorf on Golf," "Dorf and the 
First Games of Mt. Olympus" and "Dorf's Golf Bible." 
</P>
</TEXT>
