<P>
LEWIS MAY MISS GOODWILL GAMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Carl Lewis said today that he will not try to "bully my way" into the 1990 
Goodwill Games, despite a ruling that excludes those who don't compete in next 
year's national outdoor championships. 
</P>
<P>
The rule was passed by the International Competition Committee of The Athletics 
Congress. The Goodwill Games are in Seattle July 20-Aug. 5. 
</P>
<P>
"If they want me to be there, I'll be there. If not, I won't be there," said 
Lewis, a six-time Olympic medalist. 
</P>
<P>
Lewis boycotted this year's championships in his hometown of Houston because of 
"ideological differences" with TAC, the national governing body for the sport. 
</P>
<P>
He said he does not plan to compete in the 1990 national championships, to be 
held in California in June, because he will not be prepared to run until July. 
</P>
