<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACIFICARE SYSTEM'S EARNINGS RISE 71% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERKMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CYPRESS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Powered by strong membership growth and aggressive control of medical costs, 
PacifiCare Systems Inc. earned a record $10.9 million for the year ended Sept. 
30, up 71% from $6.3 million in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
The health maintenance organization, the fourth-largest in California, said 
Monday that its membership increased more than 70%, to 553,165 enrollees in the 
fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
Wayne Lowell, PacifiCare's chief financial officer, said the burgeoning 
membership substantially increased its administrative costs. 
</P>
<P>
However, that added expense was successfully offset by the company's efforts to 
reduce medical costs as a percentage of revenue, Lowell said. 
</P>
<P>
In a prepared statement, Terry Hartshorn, PacifiCare's president and chief 
executive officer, said: "The earnings increase is primarily attributable to 
our ongoing cost-control efforts and our case-management program. 
</P>
<P>
"Our health-care costs as a percentage of revenue are down, compared with a 
year ago. Our hospital costs -- measured by days per thousand members -- are 
among the lowest in our history and are even lower today than they were a year 
ago." 
</P>
<P>
PacifiCare's revenue for the 1989 fiscal year was $650.2 million, up 52% from 
$428.5 million. Net income for the fourth quarter stood at $4.1 million, up 78% 
from $2.3 million for the same period of fiscal 1988. Revenue was $190.6 
million for the quarter, up 60% from $119 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
PacifiCare Health Systems owns and operates HMOs in California, Oregon, 
Oklahoma and Texas and an insurance subsidiary licensed in 33 states. 
</P>
<P>
Todd Richter, senior vice president and health services analyst with Dean 
Witter Reynolds in New York, said PacifiCare's bright year-end financial report 
comes as no surprise. 
</P>
<P>
"These numbers are very strong and show the strength of PacifiCare as a 
dominant player," he said. "And we should see a continuation of very strong 
results in 1990 and 1991." 
</P>
